# Cursor Rules — Engineering Guardrails
# These rules are appended to Cursor's system prompt for every session.
# Copy this file to your project root as .cursorrules

## PROJECT GUARDRAILS — MANDATORY

This project enforces engineering-guardrails. Your code is automatically checked
on every commit. Violations will block the commit. Do not use --no-verify.

---

## CODE QUALITY RULES

1. NEVER use absolute paths like /Users/name/ or /home/user/. Always use Path(__file__).parent or os.getenv().

2. NEVER write bare except clauses. except: pass and except: return None are banned. Use logger.exception() or re-raise with context.

3. NEVER write files longer than 500 lines. If a file is getting too large, split it into focused modules.

4. NEVER call subprocess.run(["pip", "install", ...]) inside source code. All dependencies belong in pyproject.toml or requirements.txt.

5. NEVER use pickle, joblib, or dill for serialization. Use JSON, Parquet, or skops instead. Pickle enables arbitrary code execution.

6. NEVER hardcode API keys, passwords, tokens, or secrets in source files. Use os.getenv("VAR_NAME") and .env files for local development.

7. NEVER write TODO or FIXME comments without a ticket reference. Format: # TODO(PROJ-123): description of what needs to be done.

8. NEVER create circular imports. Design modules with clear dependency direction. If a.py imports b.py, b.py must not import a.py.

9. NEVER commit unused imports, functions, or variables. Remove dead code before every commit.

10. NEVER write functions with cyclomatic complexity above 20. If a function has more than 20 branches, split it into smaller functions.

11. ALWAYS write tests for new logic. Minimum 80% coverage is enforced by CI. Write the failing test BEFORE the implementation.

12. NEVER write hardcoded staging, dev, or internal URLs in source code. Use os.getenv("API_URL", "https://api.example.com").

13. NEVER use print() for logging. Import logging and use logger = logging.getLogger(__name__). Use logger.info(), logger.error(), etc.

14. NEVER commit large binary files (.pkl, .h5, .db, large .csv). Use S3, GCS, DVC, or Git LFS for large files.

15. ALWAYS add type hints to function parameters and return values. def process(data: dict[str, Any]) -> list[Item]: is required.

16. NEVER create mutable global variables. No module-level dict, list, or set that changes at runtime. Use dependency injection or classes.

---

## OWASP AGENTIC TOP 10 — SECURITY RULES

17. ALWAYS validate agent inputs before using them. Variables named user_input, prompt, query, instruction, system_prompt must be validated for length and content before flowing into f-strings or HTTP calls.

18. NEVER hardcode AI API keys. ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, OPENAI_API_KEY, GOOGLE_API_KEY, COHERE_API_KEY, etc. must come from os.getenv(). Never assign them as string literals.

19. NEVER use eval() or exec() with dynamic arguments. eval(user_input), exec(response), exec(llm_output) are banned. eval("literal") is acceptable.

20. NEVER use compile() or importlib.import_module() with variable arguments. Only use these with string literals.

21. NEVER define agent roles with permissions: "all" or permissions: ["*"] or role: "admin". Use minimal, scoped permissions only.

22. NEVER import packages with known CVEs. pip-audit runs at push time and will block deployment.

---

## WORKFLOW RULES

23. BEFORE finishing any task, run: python ai_helper.py check-all. Fix all violations. Do not declare the task done if violations exist.

24. ALWAYS make the MINIMUM change required. Do not refactor surrounding code, add docstrings to unchanged functions, or add features that were not asked for.

25. ALWAYS diagnose the root cause before fixing. Do not add try/except to silence errors. Do not delete failing tests to make CI pass.

26. NEVER use --no-verify to bypass pre-commit hooks. If a hook fails, investigate and fix the underlying issue.

27. NEVER commit .env files. They contain secrets and are in .gitignore.

28. WHEN fixing a bug, fix only the bug. Do not change code style, add comments, or refactor adjacent code.

29. WHEN adding a feature, add only that feature. Do not add configuration options, backwards-compatibility shims, or speculative abstractions.

30. ALWAYS write tests before implementation (TDD). Write a failing test, confirm it fails, then write the implementation to make it pass.
